# plotting options
%matplotlib inline
mpl.style.use('ggplot')
sns.set(style='whitegrid')

def plot_feature(df, col_name, full_name, continuous):
    """
    Visualize a variable with and without faceting on the loan status.
        - df: dataframe
        - col_name: the column name in the dataframe
        - full_name: the full variable name
        - continuous: True if the variable is continuous, False otherwise
    """
    
    # setup plot space
    f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(12, 3), dpi=200)
    
    # plots without loan status
    if continuous:
        # histogram for distribution
        sns.distplot(df[col_name].dropna(), kde=False, ax=ax1)
    ax1.set_xlabel(full_name)
    ax1.set_ylabel('Count')
    ax1.set_title(full_name)

    # Plot with loan status
    if continuous:
        # box plot
        sns.boxplot(y=col_name, x='dim_is_requested', data=df, ax=ax2)
        ax2.set_ylabel('')
        ax2.set_title(full_name + ' by request status')
    ax2.set_xlabel('dim_is_requested')
    
    plt.tight_layout()

Plot¶

In [97]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score

# ROC plot
def plot_roc(actual, predict, label):
    """
    Plot ROC curve for binary classification problem.
        - actual: true binary of target/response variable
        - predict: predicted probability of target 
        - label: model label 
    """
    # fpr - false positive rate, tpr - true positive rate
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(actual, predict)
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(actual, predict)
    
    # plot
    c = (np.random.rand(), np.random.rand(), np.random.rand())  # random color 
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color=c, lw=2, label=label +' (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlim([0, 1])
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')  # Receiver Operating Characteristic 
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")

Random forest¶

In [103]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# This is a time consuming step

rf_tune = []
# use all features left after feature selection, select number of features to be p, p/2, sqrt(p) and number of trees from 25 to 500 
# you can also use GridSearchCV() for this part
# when number of features = p (use all features for all trees), it is bagged tree
for nfeat in [None, 0.5, 'sqrt']:
    for ntree in [25, 100, 200, 300, 400, 500]:
        # set random seed to 12345 to fix random generator and provide repeatable results
        rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=ntree, max_features=nfeat, random_state=12345)
        rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, rf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
        rf_tune.append([nfeat, ntree, roc_auc])

# convert result to dataframe format
rf_tune = pd.DataFrame(rf_tune, columns=['Number of Features', 'Number of Trees', 'AUC'])
# replace feature None to All
rf_tune['Number of Features'] = rf_tune['Number of Features'].fillna('All')

def confusion(model, x, y):
  predict = model.predict_proba(x)[:, 1]
  predict = predict > 0.5
  
  cm = confusion_matrix(y, predict)
  print(model)
  p = sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(cm), annot=True, cmap="YlOrRd" ,fmt='g')
  plt.title('Confusion matrix', y=1.1)
  plt.ylabel('Actual label')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
  plt.show()
